An investigation into the supply and demand for The Video Streaming Market

By Samuel Summers

In less than 2 decades since the introduction of Netflix as a niche alternative to traditional movie renting, the global video streaming market has transformed into a massive global industry valued at over £190b as of Feb 2026. Once dominated by Netflix, the market has evolved into a highly competitive oligopoly with firms competing on price and technological advancements. Today the market is dominated by a handful of large firms, namely Disney+, Prime video, netflix and apple tv which make up 52-58% of market share.














Demand
Demand is defined as the quantity of a good or service that consumers are both willing and able to buy at a given price and quantity over a specific period of time. Demand in essence is the desire to own a product, backed up by the financial capability to do so.

There are various factors that influence the demand for a specific streaming platform and firms use these factors to their advantage in an effort to gain users, increase their market share and overall, make more profit. These factors are:

Price
As shown by the law of demand, a decrease in price will cause a movement along the demand curve, increasing demand. Due to the relatively inelastic nature of demand, due to strong brand loyalty as well as difficulty to cancel (however, becoming more easy due to gov. regulation), a change in price will not affect the demand greatly.
This is shown by the aggressive price increases in recent years called “streamflation”. For example, Netflix has raised its premium streaming tier drastically from about £12.99 in 2016 to £23.99 in the space of 7 years.
This aggressive pricing however has had a limited impact on the demand for netflix however, has had a limited impact on the demand as the subscriber count during this time period has risen sharply from 80m to 260m in the 7 year span, a 225% increase.

Income
For most products (normal goods), an increase in consumer disposable income leads to an increase in demand, shifting the demand curve right and increasing the quantity demanded. However, streaming can act as a relatively inexpensive substitute to entertainment like cinema. This means streaming services are not entirely dependent on the state of the economy.
This was shown most notably during the covid 19 pandemic in 2020, where a drop in disposable income by 4.3% did not cause any noticeable change to the growing subscriber count of Netflix. Whereas, the demand for clothes, an elastic good, was noticeably impacted during this period - according to the McKinsey Global Fashion Index, global fashion industry profits declined by approximately 90% in 2020.

Tastes and Fashion
If a product becomes more fashionable or consumer preferences change, the demand curve will shift rightwards, affecting the quantity demanded as well as raising price.
This was shown to affect streaming services again during the covid-19 lockdowns where “binge-watching” became more popular, a change in consumer tastes, which caused a large increase in the number of subscribers to Netflix.
This was also affected by the release of popular releases such as squid games and stranger things which caused large spikes in subscriber counts.

Advertising
Successful advertising to a consumer market increases brand awareness, thus making demand more inelastic and shifting the demand curve outwards.
For example, Disney famously spent an estimated $250m to advertise the launch of their streaming service disney+, utilising its current capital investment (namely in its theme parks and billboards) to drive over 10 million signups to the platform on its first day of operation.

Population
As population increases so does demand as the target market of a product naturally increases in size, causing an outwards shift in demand. An increase in a target market due to technological advancements also causes the same effect.
This was shown in where the global expansion of high-speed internet (required for streaming) opened up large new populations to streaming services. Streaming platforms due to this are experiencing the majority of their growth now in highly populated developing countries across Asia and Africa - this has caused an increase from 2.6 to 5.8 million subscribed users to Netflix in Africa alone, however as the services are offered at lower prices in this areas (to capture a larger market share), this increase in demand has not caused a large increase in the revenue received by Netflix.


