Supply
Supply is defined as the quantity of a good or service that producers are both willing and able to offer for sale at a given price over a specific time period. According to the Law of supply, there is a direct relationship between P and QS so, assuming all other factors remain the same, theory suggests an increase in supply will cause an increase in QD and therefore suppliers (in this case disney+, netflix etc) are incentivised to, at a small scale, expand their collection of movies and tv shows and in the bigger picture, grow their infrastructure.

Like demand, many factors influence the supply of a product. These factors are:

Cost of production
A firm’s supply curve is directly related to its cost of production. If input costs such as labour, raw materials or licensing increase, profit margins per unit supplied decrease. This makes production less prof	itable at any given price level causing a left shift and a decrease in supply, which leads to less QD.
The primary cost in this industry is licensing. Netflix for example, spent a 74% split of their 2022 $2.6B costs on cost of revenues (i.e the cost to supply a product); 54% of this was spent on licensing.
In order to cut these fixed costs, Netflix (and other streaming services) must either reduce the number of content (reducing quality and therefore demand) or create their own content which has proved very profitable and effective in the case of Netflix, with 72% of users reporting having watched a Netflix original series within the first 2 quarters of 2022

Technology
Advancements in productivity increase productivity and efficiency, allowing firms to produce a higher output at a lower variable cost, this causes a rightwards shift in supply. As such large streaming companies like Netflix spend roughly 10% of their TC in research and development into technological advancements.
As streaming relies heavily on cloud computing, over the last decade, research into video compression (for example AV1 in part developed by amazon and netflix) has allowed streaming platforms to provide a higher quality service in the form of higher definition videos at a lower cost due to less compute power being required to serve the same amount of streaming. This has increased the productive capacity of streaming platforms.

Gov. Tax and Subsidies
A gov. Tax on a firm increases its cost of production which decreases profitability, therefore incentivising producers not to supply and causing a left shift, decreasing supply. Conversely, a gov. subsidy is a financial grant given to a firm, encouraging supply, this lowers cost of production and shifts supply left, increasing supply
Many governments offer tax relief to attract film and television productions in their country as it is beneficial to the local economy, creating jobs and increasing cultural influence. For example, the UK gov. offers HETV (high end television) tax relief in which streaming companies are allowed to claim large tax rebates on production costs incurred within the UK. This directly incentivises streaming platforms looking to reduce their reliance on licensing to supply their own content from British studios
Gov. subsidies increase supply (outward shift) causing an increase in quantity demanded.

What has happened to price and quantity?
In recent years, the global video streaming market has experienced simultaneous shifts in both supply and demand. This has led to dramatic adjustments in both the equilibrium price and quantity, causing an increase in the total aggregate revenue of this market to rise by approx. 212% from $48b dollars to $137b between 2019 and 2026. Even accounting for inflation, at a total rate of 30% between the 7 years, this is a huge increase, reflecting the on average doubling of subscriber counts of all major streaming services during this time period.






